Joseph,<br><br>
Cook is right. As long as his squad leader  hollered &quot;dung lai&quot; (stop), and they continued running, the proper rule of engagement was to shoot those people - even if they were running away. It doesn't matter if it was a *free fire zone* either. The civilians knew that particular rule of engagement. This sort of thing happened at least two times (both victims were women) while I was with Charley company. The one man I remember - also a M60 gunner - broke down into tears. <br><br>
I am very sensitive about the subject of civilian casualties in the Vietnam War. I am very cautious in that I don't like to beat my fellow vets over the head with the issue. I say this as an NCO who knew right from wrong. There were many others who knew right from wrong. I *did* see many things done which were wrong.<br><br>
As far as what Cook has termed &quot;lies and deceptions by communist sympathizers&quot; back home in the US, I disagree. I cite the example of the 30,000 members of the Vietnam Veterans against The War who demonstrated against the slaughter of people we were attempting to give &quot;freedom&quot;.<br>
These (VVAW) were not hand wringing liberals, either.<br><br>
I am going to scroll back to find a very early message in this thread and will post it and a comment shortly.<br><br>

